g it in terms of each major diagenetic process. Included are the derivations of basic rate equations for diffusion, compaction, pore-water flow, burial advection, bioturbation, adsorption, radioactive decay, and especially chemical and biochemical reactions. Drawing on examples from the recent literature on continental-margin, pelagic, and non-marine sediments, he then illustrates the power of these diagenetic models in the study of such deposits.The book is intended not only for earth scientists studying sediments and sedimentary rocks, but also for researchers in fields such as radioactive waste disposal, petroleum and economic geology, environmental pollution, and sea-floor engineering.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDiagenesis. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / General.2bisacsh  aG-type kinetics.  aMichaelis-Menten kinetics.  aadsorption.  abacterial processes.  abioturbation.  acementation.  adenitriflcation.  aelectrical double layer.  aformation factor.  ageopolymers.  ahypersaline sediments.  aion exchange.  alake sediments.  amanganese reduction.  amethane formation.  anitrogen diagenesis.  aorganic matter decomposition.  aphosphate diagenesis.  aradioisotope diagenesis.  asalinity fluctuations.  asilica dissolution.  auseful porosity.  azero point of charge.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691209401zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209401423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209401.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEB